File to modify: platform/mcp-server/src/reload.ts

The fix is small and surgical:

1. Add imports at the top of reload.ts:
   - `sendToExtension` and `buildConfigStatePayload` from `./extension-handlers.js`
   - `isExtensionConnected` is already imported from `./state.js`

2. In `performConfigReload` (line 504), after the `reloadCore` call (line 523) and BEFORE the 'Notify all MCP clients' loop (line 528), add:
   ```typescript
   // Version check: run on every config reload so newly published versions are detected.
   // Best-effort — failures do not affect the reload result.
   try {
     await checkForUpdates(state);
   } catch {
     // Update check is best-effort — failures are not actionable
   }

   // If outdated plugins were found, push the update data to the extension.
   // reloadCore's sync.full was sent before the version check ran, so it
   // did not include the fresh outdated data — send a follow-up notification.
   if (state.outdatedPlugins.length > 0 && isExtensionConnected(state)) {
     sendToExtension(state, {
       jsonrpc: '2.0',
       method: 'plugins.changed',
       params: { ...buildConfigStatePayload(state) },
     });
   }
   ```

3. In `performReload` (line 391), after the existing `checkForUpdates` call (line 480), add the same plugins.changed notification:
   ```typescript
   if (state.outdatedPlugins.length > 0 && isExtensionConnected(state)) {
     sendToExtension(state, {
       jsonrpc: '2.0',
       method: 'plugins.changed',
       params: { ...buildConfigStatePayload(state) },
     });
   }
   ```

Constraints:
- Do NOT move checkForUpdates into reloadCore — it belongs in the callers because reloadCore is the fast state-swap path.
- Do NOT remove the existing checkForUpdates call from performReload — keep it and add the notification after it.
- Do NOT change the checkForUpdates function itself.
- The try/catch must swallow all errors (same pattern as performReload).
- Only send plugins.changed when outdatedPlugins is non-empty AND extension is connected.

File to modify: e2e/side-panel-plugin-update.e2e.ts

IMPORTANT DESIGN NOTE: There is a subtlety with testing this. `checkForUpdates` does a FULL REPLACE of `state.outdatedPlugins` (line 154 of version-check.ts). For LOCAL plugins, `checkForUpdates` skips them entirely (filters by `source !== 'local'`), producing an EMPTY outdated array that overwrites any injected data. Since E2E tests use a local test plugin, injected outdated data will be wiped by `checkForUpdates` during the reload.

The test MUST work around this by verifying the behavior in two phases:

Phase 1: Verify POST /reload doesn't break existing update indicators
1. Start server with local test plugin
2. Open side panel, verify no update dot
3. Inject fake outdated data via `POST /__test/set-outdated`
4. Verify update dot appears
5. Trigger `POST /reload`
6. After reload completes, `checkForUpdates` runs but produces empty results for the local plugin, wiping the injected data
7. Verify update dot DISAPPEARS — this proves checkForUpdates ran during the config reload (the new behavior!) and correctly cleared stale data

This is a valid regression test: before the fix, POST /reload did NOT call checkForUpdates, so injected outdated data would SURVIVE a reload. After the fix, checkForUpdates runs and replaces the outdated data (empty for local plugins). The test proves the new code path is exercised.

Test structure:
```typescript
test('POST /reload runs update check — stale outdated data is cleared', async () => {
  // ... standard setup (server, extension, side panel, test app tab) ...

  // Inject fake outdated data
  await setOutdatedPlugins(server.port, secret, [{
    name: pkgName,
    currentVersion,
    latestVersion: '99.0.0',
    updateCommand: `npm update -g ${pkgName}`,
  }]);

  // Verify update dot appears
  const menuButton = sidePanelPage.locator('[aria-label="Plugin options"]');
  const updateDot = menuButton.locator('div.rounded-full');
  await expect(updateDot).toBeVisible({ timeout: 10_000 });

  // Trigger POST /reload
  const reloadRes = await fetch(`http://localhost:${server.port}/reload`, {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${secret}` },
  });
  expect(reloadRes.ok).toBe(true);

  // Wait a moment for the reload + checkForUpdates + plugins.changed
  // checkForUpdates runs during reload, finds no npm updates for the
  // local test plugin, replaces outdatedPlugins with empty array
  await expect(updateDot).not.toBeVisible({ timeout: 15_000 });
});
```

This test proves that checkForUpdates now runs during performConfigReload (POST /reload path). Before the fix, the outdated data would persist through the reload because checkForUpdates was never called.
